reviewText: I'm not sure how anyone can rate these episodes or this last season already,  since these episodes haven't even been broadcast yet, but I have high hopes for this last season of what has been to me a fun and entertaining show. I am disappointed that Syfy decided to cancel yet another excellent show, most likely to be replaced with more of their WWF or reality drivel, but I am looking forward to this fifth season of Warehouse 13. I'm sure they will go out in style.
Hopefully the price on this "SEASON" #5 shall drop due to the season c/o only six (6) episodes to wrap-up series. SY-FY shot themselves in foot with this cancellation!

Warehouse 13 is one of my favorite sci-fi series; it's a great combination of comedy, drama, action, and some very novel ideas. Imagine that objects can have powers: Brushing your hair with Marilyn Monroe's hairbrush will turn your hair color to platinum blonde; W.C. Fields' juggling balls will make you drunk...
Great cast, fascinating plot lines with surprising twists, and well done character growth make this a "must own" series. I have bought all five seasons, and my wife and I sat down and watched them all from season 1 to the last episode.

That was totally unbelievable. I did like, and it made me cry, when Artie had the heart to heart with the Warehouse & the Warehouse rolling an apple to him. I think that was the most believable and fitting part that made any kind of sense in wrapping up Warehouse 13. In regards to Claudia, it only made sense that she would take the place of Mrs Frederic. I did not like where Claudia first wanted it then she didn't. It wasn't believable to me because it was obvious where the story was going. I have to say I really love this show. I started out not really knowing what to think, especially for a sci-fi mini-series, but it took my imagination and ended up being one of the greatest sci fi shows I've seen in a long time.

The main male lead is pretty obnoxious, being one of those man child things that seem to be so common in tv and movies these days, and unfortunately also in real life. The other main character is a female that I also have a hard time standing. She's got this obnoxious propensity to look like a puppy dog getting a good pet from someone whenever they give her a compliment or even so much as act like a normal human being towards her.

You might be asking yourself with this incredible lineup of main characters why I am rating it a 5 stars. This comes from the fact that the supporting characters are brilliant, a psychotic and brilliant computer hacker, and a scrooge type of old man that hates newfangled technology.

The thing that really makes this show work is the idea behind it. If you've watched any of the librarian movies, then you'll know the basic story. a secret agency that protects artifacts with magical abilities. But they don't get too weighed down in confusing storylines. So it's mostly just a show exploring really interesting objects created by famous people throughout history.

So, definitely give it a watch, and I hope you enjoy it as much as I did!

So, I wanted to write this as a general comment on the really harsh negative reviews of this 5th and final season... it was meant to be a fun farewell to the series from Jack Kenny, the producers, writers and actors. The emotional peak of this show was in season 4, which had some of the finest writing and acting in the entire series. There was immense loss, death and devastation in Season 4 which marked an important evolution in both the writing and acting in the series, but in their final season, it appears they wanted to just have fun to close out the series.

Jack Kenny, the producers and writers were given a gift of a 5th season with a shortened 6 episodes to work with to resolve the Season 4 cliffhangers as well as produce the episodes they always wanted to produce but never had the chance to. For those who really critique how un-serious and absurd this season was, perhaps you need to revisit some of the old Warehouse 13 DVDs, particularly listening to the commentaries and/or podcasts.  There was a lot of meta/self-referential humor in the 5th season that you might understand and appreciate to if you listened to the commentaries/podcasts from the past seasons. The Spanish Telenovela and the Ren-Faire episodes were all fun romps into the worlds the producers, writers and actors always wanted to explore. They really weren't that different from the Fargo-from-Eureka-Video-Game or the Hard-Boiled-Detective episodes.

***SEASON 5 SPOILER ALERT***
The series didn't end exactly the way I wanted it to, particularly the sudden romantic relationship that developed between our beloved main characters. I thought the brother-sister relationship of Myka and Pete was something fun and refreshing instead of forcing a "will-they-won't-they-Ross-and-Rachel" type of thing and hitting the fans over the head with it every episode. I would have preferred that they were discussing in the first half of Season 5; having a child together and raising him or her with 2 adults in a platonic relationship. However, I do understand that Jack Kenny, et al. wanted to give the fans who really wanted Myka and Pete to get together a payoff for sticking through 5 seasons. I also thought the Season 4 Paracelsus cliffhanger was too conveniently wrapped up in the first episode and the Claire story-arc could have used a bit more fleshing out.

All that being said, and understanding that Universal CP & SyFy could have just ended the series after Season 4 and not lost any more money on it, I am glad that Jack Kenny, the writers, producers and actors were able to end the series on their terms. I am also glad Jack Kenny got to appear in the final scene of the final episode.

I like watching shows when the series has ended, or is about to---to see everything episode after espisode, like an extended movie.  Such was the case with Warehouse 13, but it took re-watching the pilot, after the Final Episode, to see how far the series has sunk.  SyFy appears to have gotten bored.

Of course the very premise of the show is questionable at best---if even one of these artifacts is as dangerous as they are demonstrated to be, why would you put them all together in one place where the chances of some undesireable getting their hands on them, any of them, would be so much easier than having to traipse the world?  So, what we've got is something of a detective fantasy, where instead of high tech gizmos with which to solve crimes (or Grimm Fairy tale animals in real life) here the "crimes" are caused by artifacts that either someone has come into possession of accidentally, or has sought them out for illicit gain.  Secret Service agents Latimer and Bering are sent out on one mission after another to "snag, bag, and tag" these artifacts.

The early episodes, of the first two seasons or so, were a marvel of steam punk aesthetic paired with action adventure.  Remember when the Warehouse had a zipline?  The big old computer with the ancient typewriter keys?  The cast grew--nicely I thought---but the fantasy began to fade, the steampunk slipped ever further into the background.  I can't even really remember seeing much of it anywhere in Season 5.  And it's not just  that.  The whole show was getting ever more stupid (and it wasn't very literary from the start...) well before Season 4 came to a conclusion with Latimer acting like a boy-man moron.  Season 5 resolves the last episode in the first show, then it pops back and forth until---way too soon---we're at the sixth and final episode---the  Very End, which is billed as a sort of flash back (you know, where they run clips of past episodes) but in fact all of the stuff recalled consists either of out-takes or cuts, or stuff put together specifically for this show,, yet to look as if it happened in previous episodes, so it's not really flash backs in the usual sense.  Nice touch.

Still...

So it's over.  You'll want to watch these last episodes if you've watched the rest, and you won't be too terribly disappointed, but it is certainly sad to see how far the show fell from the tree that produced it, from the spell casting charm of the early episodes.

A Note:  I streamed all of season 5 as I have the others and these are all full episodes.  I found that SyFy does like to sell clips on Amazon but these are all full episodes.

They force in a romance at the last second that should never, EVER have been attempted, they throw in yet another member of Claudia's family in a way that felt really random, they utilized an old villain rather than trying anything new.  The finale was disappointing in every conceivable way, particularly with what they did with Pete and Myka (which felt like it was written by someone who thought that the romance in Twilight was a little too well thought out).  If it weren't for the adorable father/daughter-esque relationship between Artie and Claudia, I would say that season 5 managed to do absolutely everything wrong.  I would recommend just pretending that the show ended after Season 4 rather than subjecting yourself to this.

I'm writing a review for the show-content as I have not yet received the DVD.
It's very sad to me that the television industry has been slowly caving in to the seeming need for senseless sex, violence and mindless craziness which seems to be the primary entertainment-diet of the average American brain these days. Such is the case with this fun and reasonably-intelligent series which, though it has plenty of violence and some sexual content, is far from mindless and can actually make you think.
In this final season, Mr. Valda, one of the Regents who govern the Warehouse, has returned from oblivion from an alternate timeline. He seeks to take over the Warehouse and move it to a new location where he can exploit the artifacts for profit and power. In the end Valda is foiled, and the season (and series) ends with the Warehouse moving to a new, undisclosed, location.
What I found most upsetting about this season of the show is that it was so short - only six episodes as opposed to the roughly 16 we are generally used to. It seems as if the people in charge of SyFy were tired of it and just threw it away! The same thing happened with Eureka which, though not quite as good in my opinion, was still a lot of fun and was really good sci-fi fantasy. At least with Eureka we got a full final season. The problem is that what this is being replaced with is material which I really don't like. I'm not a fan of reality-shows like Ghost Hunters or Ghost Mine (though I find the latter amusing enough to watch when there is absolutely nothing else on) nor do I like a steady diet of reality-competitions like Face-Off or the Jim Henson Creature Competition. And what in heck does wrestling have to do with science fiction ... anyone?
Getting back to Warehouse 13 itself, the full series is a rollicking roller-coaster ride through items psychically imbued with the essence of their original owners, where they came from and how to retrieve them. Lewis Caroll's Mirror has the soul of Alice Liddel trapped inside. W.C. Fields' juggling balls cause anyone holding them to act like they were drunk. A katana forged by the discoverer of the principle of folded steel is so sharp it can  bend light and render its wielder invisible. These and many more are the objects which the Warehouse was built to house and protect the world from. The team consists of two Secret Service agents, an FBI agent, a young genius and a psychic all led by a grumpy ex-smuggler. The stories are less about the artifacts and more about the people who have dedicated their lives to finding them and keeping them hidden. There are history lessons and plenty of references to mythology both well-known and obscure. And, for those who enjoyed Eureka, there were two crossover episodes in which a side romace between the characters of Douglas Fargo (Eureka) and Claudia Donovan (Warehouse 13) seemed to promise seeing more of both shows.
Finally, Warehouse 13 had many of the same qualities found in Doctor Who which has made that show the longest-running science-fiction television series of all time, as well as the longest scripted television series of any kind. The history they set up of the Warehouse changing hands could have been exploited if it was a cast-change which was necessary (though I don't think anyone was tired of any of the principles). It had the possibility of essentially going anywhere and to any genre, including futuristic space-opera. And the Warehouse itself is a lot like the TARDIS in many ways - a vehicle to the "endless wonder" which Mrs. Fredricks so often uses to sell life as a Warehouse Agent to prospective recruits.
All in all, Season 5 is a short and disappointing ending to series which was a lot of fun to watch. And there is nothing remotely similar coming to replace it - with the possible exception of Terry Pratchett's "The Watch" which is years away from airing. There is, however, the hope that someone will eventually pick up the story of the Warehouse with Warehouse 14.
As with the other seasons, Season 5 of Warehouse 13 is watchable by most people over the age of 10 or so. A good guage is if they like Doctor Who, they'll probably like Warehouse 13. And if you're worried about gun-violence, Warehouse Agents are armed with stun-guns called Teslas which are non-lethal.

Quick Summary:

There are "Artifacts" in the world that are powerful and dangerous.  To counter this threat the "Warehouse" has existed for centuries to protect mankind from the dangers.  Warehouse agents find these "Artifacts" and store them in the "Warehouse".  The "Warehouse" operates independently of world governments, but has to be moved for safety reasons occasionally from location to location or country to country and becomes dependant on its host nation for protection.  The current "Warehouse 13" is located in South Dakota in the United States and the Secret Service has been tasked with assisting the "Warehouse" with its mission.

I pray it's not the actors, but I have a hunch it's both bad acting and a very unnatural script. The sound like they are doing a perhaps second time read- through.

That said, I watched all five seasons. I loved the concept, the bits of history and culture woven into some fun adventures and artifacts. The concept is fantastic and I held onto that and Claudia's character more than anything. It did end when it needed to. Would love to see it come back someday with better acting and more natural relationships. Take the concept and run with it, develop it, and this may be a good show to come back and re-do (better) in a few years. Because, like I said, I love the concept and the idea of the show. Oh yes, and I LOVE LOVE LOVED everything that had H.G. Wells. She was the reason I held on to the end (even though she didn't.

This was one of the better episodes of this (the last) season.  Two investigations going on simultaneously split up the team, with Artie, Myka, and Pete being trapped in a South American telenovella (soap opera) while Claudia and Jinks investigate a fraternity initiation ritual that involves a candle artifact. Both storylines split several characters into multiple personalities which make for some nice comedy, especially when the team trapped in the television melodrama find themselves speaking rather fluent spanish. The subtitles are very amusing, but not as much as the english-speaking actors skillfully reciting their over-the-top spanish dialogue. Brazilian superstar Sonia Braga appears in a campy cameo.

Although this is a favorite show when going well, this episode, parodying Spanish telenovelas, made its point by wild, hysterical overacting, far from the usual suitable blend of mild wit and bogus science  that the show is built on. The characters remained likable, however, so all was not lost.

I have been a devoted WAREHOUSE 13 fan since Season 1.  "Each to his/her own taste" is axiomatic, so for anyone reading this review who is already a fan, no explanation is necessary; for anyone who isn't, no explanation is possible.  However, if you're unacquainted with the series, here's a quick analogy:  Remember the last scene of RAIDERS OF THE LOST ARK, in which some Pentagon janitor crates up the Ark of the Covenant and dollies it into an obscure corner of the sub-basement?  Throughout history, the Warehouses (which can be traced back to ancient Egypt) have been the repositories for similar artifacts -- though not all of them have been as sanctified as the Ark.  How about Edgar Allan Poe's quill pen?  Or Alice's looking glass?  What about the strings from Carlo Collodi's marionette woven together as a bracelet?  In the first episode of the series, Artie promises Pete and Myka "Endless Wonder" -- and the writers, directors, and cast have been delivering on that promise ever since.  The perfectly cast principals create just the right chemistry in the weekly combination of action, adventure, and more than a little humor.  So the next time you encounter a malevolent artifact, snag it, bag it, and tag it -- and ship it to WAREHOUSE 13!

This is a review and commentary about Warehouse 13.  I really like this show and am sorry to see it go (with only 6 episodes at that).  SYFY is famous for this which is one of the reasons that I dumped cable.  But I digress, for those of you that got season passes for this final season, this may interest you:

Amazon.com dropped the ball (again) with these extras that they are calling episodes which are only 6 or 7 minutes each.  I would urge you to contact amazon.com to get refunds x 2 ($1.89 each for standard def video).  They will need your order numbers which you can copy down from the emails you would have received when they notified you.  They did this before with other shows that were ending; trying to charge money for the tiniest of short extras that anyone could find online for free.

I got a full refund for the two charges because amazon.com didn't mean to charge us for it.  If you really want to pay the $1.89, go for it.  But amazon wasn't supposed to do that.  It happened before, it's happening now, and it will happen again.  You're welcome :D

As someone who was so excited seeing the previews for Warehouse 13 back in the summer of 2009; and was hooked from the Pilot episode onward, I hate to see this series come to an end; but from what this 6 minute sneak peak revealed it truly does look as though it is going out on a high note, w/ the credit and respect it deserves. As the cast and crew say many, many times over, there will never be another show like Warehouse 13. It's been a great ride for us the fans; and now we look forward to watching these last few episodes. And for those of us who rely upon Amazon Prime for access to our favorite TV viewing, it's been fantastic to have access to the episodes @ a discounted Season Pass. Warehouse 13 and Amazon Prime, it doesn't get any better.

I love Warehouse 13, This being the final season it was a bittersweet thing. When I originally watched it on TV, I was so upset that it was ending that I didn't appreciate or enjoy it as I should have. Seeing it now the thing that amazes me is how incredible it is. The writers/producers/actors stayed true to the characters and concepts of the show from beginning to end. Brilliant, engaging stories, astonishing dialogue...not many shows have so many unique voices!

It's hard to pick a favorite episode, but Claudia probably had the best story arc of the season. Her peculiar family issues have always played an important part in the show, and this season the addition of a new member of the family adds to her character's angst. The biggest surprise was the inclusion of the Pete/Myka storyline In truth I definitely saw this coming in season 2, but then they seemed to drop it. I was resigned to it never being resolved, yet here it is taking center stage once more. Brilliant!

The inclusion of the Holiday Episode makes me very happy. It's one of my top four favorites Christmas episodes pf any show ever to air on television. Kudos to the cast and crew for maintaining their excellence for five seasons. The only thing that would make me happier would be a new movie!

I'm still watching all the bonus features. There are so many podcasts and special bits included that it will take me some time to watch them all. Suffice to say, you'll laugh as much watching that as you will watching the episodes. I will miss these characters and I'm glad I can rematch them again and again.
